<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-428-568  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 428 568.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  May 7 1990 n299 p8(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft strategy: harmonizing OS/2 Windows.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Haight, Timothy.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microsoft Corp seeks to increase the appeal of its OS/2 operatingsystem by making it more compatible with its Windows graphicaluser interface for DOS.andP;  Microsoft with provide certain softwaredevelopers with a kit that makes it possible to port Windowsapplications to Presentation Manager, OS/2's graphical userinterface.andP;  When OS/2 2.0 is shipped, possibly by the end of 1990,all Windows applications will be able to run with it without beingmodified.andP;  An OS/2 that is more compatible with Windows willbenefit the user by increasing the number of applications thatwill run on OS/2.andP;  Microsoft's new developer's kit will provide arun-time translation layer that maps Windows applicationsprogramming interfaces (API) into OS/2 APIs.andP;  The kit can bepurchased with the next release of the OS/2 2.0 developer's kit,in Jun 1990, and it will also be available in a future Windowsdeveloper's kit.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   OS/2 Presentation Manager (Graphical user interface) (usage)Microsoft Windows for OS/2 (Graphical user interface) (productenhancement).andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentEnhancementsWindowingNetworksSoftware PublishersSoftware PackagesSoftware DesignGraphical User InterfaceOperating Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>